 Bull-rout 
 Myoxocephalus scorpius
Order: Scorpaeniformes
Family: Cottidae

External appearance
Unlike other similar fish, the bull-rout has three spines on its head. When spawning, males have a reddish belly, whereas females have a reddish-yellow belly with white spots. The fish is 20 - 30 centimetres long.

Distribution
Found in the seas of northern Europe.

Diet
Eats crustaceans, worms, small fish and juveniles of other fish.

Development
Spawns from December to March. It deposits its eggs in clumps on rocks.

Fishing
This species is of minor importance to both commercial fishing and anglers. 

Interesting facts
The male guards the eggs after spawning.

